<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-545-708  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 545 708.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Wall Street Computer Review  August 1989 v6 n11 p24(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High-tech moves put S andamp; L ahead in securities chase. (NortheastSavings)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Arend, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Some savings and loan institutions are achieving a healthy returnon their investment in trading automation for dealing in a varietyof securities, despite the recent bad press and government bailoutof a large part of the industry.andP;  Northeast Savings constructed aneight-position trading room in its new headquarters in Nov 1985and now deals in fixed- and floating-rate mortgage-backedsecurities (MBS), Treasury securities, commercial paper, andcorporate bonds.andP;  The backbone of the trading desk consists of theRich TRIARCH (Trading Information Architecture) trading system andContel IPC trading turrets.andP;  Northeast Savings has $8 billion inassets and ranks in the top 20 publicly-held thrift institutions.andO;Future growth depends on emerging capital requirements and tradingregulations that start Aug 30, 1989.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Northeast Savings (automation).andO;Topic:     BankingAutomationStock MarketFinancial Services.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>